    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>Why Convert Plain Text to PDF?</h2>
      <p>
        Plain text files are the most universal digital document format. Every operating system can open a .txt file without installing additional software, and text files have remained readable for decades without format obsolescence. However, plain text lacks the visual structure that makes documents presentable: there are no margins, no consistent pagination, and no guarantee that the text will render the same way on every device or printer. Converting text to PDF bridges this gap by wrapping your content in a format that preserves layout across every screen and printer in existence.
      </p>
      <p>
        PDF documents carry their own font metrics, page dimensions, and margin definitions. When you send a PDF, the recipient sees exactly what you intended regardless of their operating system, installed fonts, or display resolution. This makes PDF the preferred format for archiving text documents, submitting reports, sharing meeting notes, and printing manuscripts. The conversion process does not alter your words; it simply places them inside a container that guarantees consistent rendering.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>When You Need a PDF of Text Content</h2>
      <p>
        Several common scenarios call for converting plain text to PDF. Archiving is one of the most important: organizations that store records for compliance or legal purposes often require PDF/A format because it is an ISO standard for long-term preservation. Printing is another: sending a .txt file to a printer produces output with tiny margins, no page numbers, and inconsistent line breaks, while a PDF prints with proper margins and clean page boundaries every time.
      </p>
      <p>
        Sharing formatted documents is a third reason. When you paste a plain text log, configuration file, or transcript into this tool, the resulting PDF has uniform margins, a readable font size, and automatic page breaks that prevent text from being cut off mid-line. This matters when sharing server logs with a client, exporting chat transcripts for a legal review, or turning personal notes into a document that looks polished enough to distribute.
      </p>

      <h3>Advantages of the PDF Format</h3>
      <p>
        PDF files render identically on Windows, macOS, Linux, iOS, and Android. They cannot be accidentally edited by the recipient, which protects the integrity of your content. PDF supports accessibility features such as tagged text for screen readers, and the files compress efficiently for email attachments. Unlike word processor formats that depend on installed fonts and application versions, a PDF embeds everything needed for faithful reproduction. These properties make PDF the standard output format for contracts, invoices, academic papers, government filings, and technical documentation worldwide.
      </p>

      <h3>How This Tool Preserves Your Text</h3>
      <p>
        The converter reads your input line by line and places each line into the PDF at the correct vertical position using the font size you selected. Paragraphs separated by blank lines receive additional vertical spacing. When the text reaches the bottom margin of a page, a new page is created automatically, and the content continues at the top. The tool uses Helvetica, a standard PDF base font available in every PDF reader, so no font embedding is required and the resulting file size stays small. You can adjust the font size from 8pt for dense technical content up to 16pt for large-print readability, and switch between A4 and US Letter page dimensions to match your region or printing requirements.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How does TXT to PDF conversion work in the browser?</h3>
      <p>
        The tool reads your plain text, breaks it into paragraphs and lines, then constructs a valid PDF 1.4 document using JavaScript. It handles pagination, margins, and font rendering entirely on the client side. The resulting file opens in any PDF reader.
      </p>

      <h3>Will my text data be uploaded to a server?</h3>
      <p>
        No. Everything happens locally in your browser. Your text never leaves your device. You can disconnect from the internet and the tool still works.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I change the font size and page layout?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Use the font size slider to pick any size between 8pt and 16pt. You can also toggle between A4 and US Letter page sizes to match your printing needs.
      </p>

      <h3>Does the converter preserve line breaks and paragraph spacing?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Single line breaks produce separate lines in the PDF. Double line breaks create paragraph spacing. The structure of your original text is faithfully reproduced with proper margins and pagination.
      </p>

      <h3>Is there a size limit?</h3>
      <p>
        The tool handles documents with tens of thousands of lines comfortably. The practical limit depends on browser memory. For extremely large files, processing may take a few seconds but there is no hard character limit.
      </p>

